  "summary": "While tying his shoelace, Hastings encounters Megan Barnard, who arrives by taxi carrying a small suitcase. Megan, described as having a fashionable but striking appearance with a short black bob, initially treats Hastings with suspicion and defiance. She asserts that her sister, Elizabeth \"Betty\" Barnard, was a good girl with no male friends, a statement Hastings notes was intended to mock the newspapers' tendency to idealize the dead.\n\nMegan leads Hastings into a kitchen, where Hercule Poirot joins them. Megan recognizes Poirot as a fashionable private detective. Poirot challenges Megan's previous characterization of Betty, explaining his motive to find the truth by speaking to those who knew the deceased before her death. Megan admits that while she liked Betty, she considered her a \"fool.\" She provides a photo of a blonde girl with a mischievous smile, noting that she herself is the \"plain\" sister.\n\nMegan reveals that Betty enjoyed attention from handsome men and would banter with customers at the Yellow Cat Cafe, even if she intended to marry Donald \"T\" Fraser. Although Megan initially describes Donald as a calm and steady man, Poirot probes further, suggesting he may be violent or jealous. Megan eventually agrees to be truthful, admitting that Donald is naturally jealous and struggles to understand why Betty seeks the company of other men despite her affection for him.",
